# RH Non-Trivial Zeros Locator v0.1
# Status: locator / numerical evidence / no proof yet for RH
# Date: 2026-05-20
#
# Truth boundary:
#   This is NOT a proof of the Riemann Hypothesis.
#   This is a locator pipeline for known / candidate non-trivial zeros.
#   Finite numerical agreement ≠ global no-off-ridge theorem.
#
# Core target:
#   Locate the n-th non-trivial zero:
#
#     ρ_n = 1/2 + i γ_n
#
#   by:
#     1. alpha lock:
#          α = Re(ρ) - 1/2 = 0
#
#     2. theta midpoint locator:
#          θ(T_0) / π = n - 3/2
#
#     3. Hardy Z refinement:
#          Z(t) = exp(i θ(t)) ζ(1/2 + i t)
#          find γ_n such that Z(γ_n)=0
#
#     4. xi local basin check:
#          ξ(s) = 1/2 · s(s-1) · π^(-s/2) · Γ(s/2) · ζ(s)
#          R(α,t)=|ξ(1/2+α+it)|²
#
#   Expected local shape at a critical-line zero:
#
#          R(α,γ_n) ≈ A_n α² + B_n α⁴ + ...
#
#   centered_single_well means:
#
#          R(+α,γ_n) = R(-α,γ_n)
#          R(0,γ_n)=0
#
#   This supports the local α=0 locator.
#   It does NOT prove RH.
# ============================================================
# LOCATOR EQUATIONS
# ============================================================
Non-trivial zero:
  ζ(ρ)=0
  0 < Re(ρ) < 1
Alpha coordinate:
  α(ρ) = Re(ρ) - 1/2
Critical-line form:
  α(ρ)=0
  ρ_n = 1/2 + i γ_n
Riemann-Siegel theta:
  θ(t)
    =
    Im log Γ(1/4 + i t/2)
    - (t/2) log π
Hardy Z:
  Z(t)
    =
    exp(i θ(t)) ζ(1/2 + i t)
Root condition:
  Z(γ_n)=0
  ⇔ ζ(1/2+iγ_n)=0
Naive smooth counting:
  N_sm(T)
    =
    T/(2π) log(T/(2π))
    - T/(2π)
    + 7/8
Naive locator:
  N_sm(T)=n
Corrected half-jump / theta midpoint locator:
  θ(T_0)/π = n - 3/2
Asymptotic half-jump locator for very high N:
  N_sm(T_0)=n-1/2
Average spacing:
  Δ(T)
    =
    2π / log(T/(2π))
Bracket:
  I_n =
    [T_0 - kΔ(T_0), T_0 + kΔ(T_0)]
Hardy refinement:
  find γ_n ∈ I_n such that:
    Z(γ_n)=0
Newton polish:
  t_{m+1}
    =
    t_m - Z(t_m)/Z'(t_m)
Secant polish:
  t_{m+1}
    =
    t_m
    - Z(t_m)(t_m-t_{m-1})
      /(Z(t_m)-Z(t_{m-1}))
Final localized zero:
  ρ_n = 1/2 + iγ_n
